<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-12-03T09:44:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-12-03T09:44:00-05:00" n="349" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d349">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">882.001/54: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Liberia</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Reber</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Monrovia</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-12-03T14:00:00-00:44">December 3, 1930—2
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received 3:15 p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>169. President King has just informed me that he will resign this
                            afternoon at 3 o’clock. Edwin Barclay, the Secretary of State and lawful
                            successor, will assume the Presidency.</p>
                        <pb facs="0473" n="379" xml:id="pg_379"/>
                        <p>President added that he was compelled to resign on account of the
                            opposition to his reform program and made no further comment on the
                            Secretary’s memorandum.</p>
                        <p>Barclay is openly anti-white and opposed to the International
                            Commission’s recommendations. I shall await instructions before calling
                            upon the new President.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Reber</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>